         <abstract>
            <p>The differential-difference equation $t\upsilon'(t) + \upsilon(t - 1) = 0, \quad t &gt; 1, \\ \upsilon(t) = 0, \quad t &lt; 0, \\ \upsilon(t) = \text{constant}, \quad 0 \leqq t \leqq 1,$$ can be solved by the Monte-Carlo method, for the initial condition $\upsilon(t) = e^{-\gamma}, 0 \leqq t \leqq 1$, where the $\upsilon(t)$ represent the probability density of a random variable: $$t = \lim {n \rightarrow \infty} \sum^n_{i=1} \Pi^i_{j = 1} x_j$$, where the $x_j$ are independent and uniformly distributed on $(0, 1)$.</p>
          </abstract>
